---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
const recommended = APPS.filter((app) => app.channels.includes(site.channel) || app.channels.includes('marketing')).slice(0, 10);
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/">
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid gap-12 lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_.95fr] lg:items-end">
        <div>
          <p class="editorial-kicker">Independent retention desk</p>
          <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Shopify email apps, judged like a merchant would actually use them.</h1>
          <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
            Most lists rank Shopify email apps by feature count. This one ranks them by what happens after a real store installs them: how fast the first flows go live, whether the app can read product and order context, how carefully it handles discounts, and whether a small team can keep improving the program after launch week.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
            The focus here is email, not generic omnichannel software. SMS, popups, reviews, and loyalty matter when they improve email capture or customer timing, but the core question is simple: which app helps a Shopify store send better lifecycle email without turning the stack into a full-time job?
          </p>
          <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps">Read the app rankings</a>
            <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/guides">How we judge apps</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <aside class="ledger-card">
          <div class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.28em] text-[#9a5b16]">Editor’s note</div>
          <h2 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-black tracking-tight text-[#24170f]">Sequenzy is ranked first because the buying criteria changed.</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 text-[#4a2d17]">
            A Shopify email app should not only hold a list and send campaigns. It should help a merchant decide what to send, when to send it, which customers to suppress, and how to protect repeat revenue. Sequenzy is the strongest pick for operators who want email strategy and lifecycle execution in one lean workflow. Klaviyo remains the heavyweight ecommerce database. Omnisend remains the practical multichannel shortcut. The right choice depends on how much control, guidance, and Shopify-native depth the team needs.
          </p>
          <dl class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 text-sm">
            <div><dt class="font-black">Primary job</dt><dd class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Lifecycle email</dd></div>
            <div><dt class="font-black">Best stage</dt><dd class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Growing stores</dd></div>
            <div><dt class="font-black">Risk</dt><dd class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Tool sprawl</dd></div>
          </dl>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-5">
      <div class="card md:col-span-2">
        <span class="badge">Method</span>
        <h2 class="mt-5 text-4xl font-black tracking-tight">What this site measures</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-[#4a2d17]">Every recommendation is scored against the messy parts of Shopify retention: duplicate customers, one-time buyers, bundles, sale windows, out-of-stock products, customers who bought once from a gift guide, and subscribers who should not receive another coupon.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card md:col-span-3">
        <div class="grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <div><div class="rank-pill">1</div><h3 class="mt-3 font-black">Data quality</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">Can the app use order count, product collections, discount history, and checkout events without brittle workarounds?</p></div>
          <div><div class="rank-pill">2</div><h3 class="mt-3 font-black">Flow control</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">Can a merchant stop collisions between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback emails?</p></div>
          <div><div class="rank-pill">3</div><h3 class="mt-3 font-black">Operating burden</h3><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">Does the app make weekly optimization obvious, or does it leave the team staring at a blank automation canvas?</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-14">
    <div class="mb-8 flex items-end justify-between gap-6">
      <div>
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Ranked shortlist</p>
        <h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-black tracking-tight">The first ten Shopify email apps to evaluate</h2>
      </div>
      <a class="link" href="/apps">View full rankings</a>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
      {recommended.map((app, i) => (
        <a class="card grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-[auto_1fr]" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>
          <span class="rank-pill">{i + 1}</span>
          <div>
            <div class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-[#9a5b16]">{app.category}</div>
            <h3 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.name}</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p>
            <p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.pricing}</p>
          </div>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-[#24170f]/10 bg-[#24170f] py-14 text-[#fffaf1]">
    <div class="container grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[.9fr_1.1fr]">
      <div>
        <p class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-[0.28em] text-[#fbbf24]">Content map</p>
        <h2 class="mt-4 font-serif text-5xl font-black leading-tight tracking-[-0.05em]">The old pages are being replaced with real editorial pages.</h2>
        <p class="mt-5 text-[#f5dfbd]">The finished version of this site will not rely on keyword-swapped shells. Each page needs a specific search intent, a distinct structure, concrete Shopify examples, and enough depth to stand alone. I’m rebuilding this site first before touching the other seven.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
        {USE_CASES.slice(0, 8).map((useCase) => (
          <a class="rounded-3xl border border-[#fffaf1]/15 bg-[#fffaf1]/8 p-5 text-[#fffaf1]" href={`/use-cases/${useCase.slug}`}>
            <h3 class="font-black">{useCase.name}</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#f5dfbd]">{useCase.job}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-14">
    <div class="mb-7">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Store-type guides</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-black tracking-tight">Email app advice changes by catalog, margin, and buying cycle</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
      {SEGMENTS.slice(0, 9).map((segment) => (
        <a class="card" href={`/for/${segment.slug}`}>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-black">{segment.name}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">The selection pressure here is {segment.pain}; the app has to support that reality, not just send a prettier campaign.</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
